[Student "S"]
{You have 13 points so you will definitely open the bidding. You don't open with a 4-card Major and you don't open with a 2-card \C suit. So this is the one distribution where you open a 3-card \D suit. Partner responds 2\C and  

Be very careful! You are tempted to now bid 2\H or 2\S. Don't give in to the temptation. That would be a <b>REVERSE</b> - bidding a second, higher-ranking suit at the 2-level. You should have at least 16 points to reverse. Besides, if you trust partner you don't need to bid either of those suits anyway. If he had a 4-card Major he probably would have shown it on his first bid. No, your next bid is clearly 2NT. Partner raises to 3NT and you pass.

North plays 3NT. East leads the \H2, West wins the \HA and returns the \H5. East takes the \HK and plays the \H7.

<b>North plays 3NT. East leads the \H2, West wins the \HA and returns the \H5. East takes the \HK and plays the \H7.</b>

Winner count: \S 2 : \H 2 : \D 2 : \C 2 : Total = 8

You are glad the defense started with \Hs, that was a suit you would have had to play yourself. You need one more winner and your first thought may be that the \Ss are going to have to split 3-3. However, that happens only about 40% of the time so you keep looking. There is one more card that might be valuable, the \CJ. If West holds the \CQ then you can make a trick out of the \CJ.

You are already in dummy with the \HJ so you lead a small \C. If West plays low you will play the \CJ which will hold the trick and become your 9th winner. If West plays his \CQ you will have the \CJ for your 9th winner later.

And if West doesn't have the \CQ at all? then you <b>STILL</b> have the possibility of a 3-3 \S split.

As you see, this time the \Ss didn't split so you had to make the \CJ to succeed. }
[Play "W"]H2

