[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "S"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "S:.AKQT3.9642.T632 QJT82.965.QT.Q74 K7.J74.A753.J985 A96543.82.KJ8.AK"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "4S"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "S"]
pass pass pass 1S 2H 4S pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "b02b48c945129a4c38e2a62825f937628f731cc430c241181754dac333c85c73"]
[Category "Practice Deals"]
[Difficulty "mixed"]
[SkillPath "practice_deals/100_miscellaneous"]
[Student "S"]
{You open 1\S. South overcalls 2\H and partner bids 4\S.

East plays 4\S. South leads \HA, \HK, \HQ.

<b>East plays 4\S. South leads \HA, \HK, \HQ.</b>

Losers: \S 1 : \H 2 : \D 1 : \C 0 : Total = 4

You have already lost the 2 \Hs and you will definitely lose the \D. So you cannot lose a \S as well. When you have 11 cards in a suit missing the King, the recommended play is to play for the drop. But the recommended play shouldn't be used on this hand because you know that North has the \SK. How do you know this? Because South has turned up with 10 points in \Hs, (the A K Q and a fifth one). If he held the \SK as well he would have had 13 points and a good suit and would have opened he bidding. But he didn't open, so he doesn't have the \SK.

Ruff the \H. Play the \D8 to dummy's \D10. If North takes the \DA win his return and enter dummy with the \DQ. When in dummy lead the \SQ and finesse North out of his \SK.

You have to listen to the bidding and draw conclusions from what is bid - and not bid. Because he passed originally you could figure out that South could not hold the \SK. Or, if you had needed to know, he could also not have had the \DA.}
[Play "W"]HA

